SIMPLE: scandal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scandal
<hw>Scan"dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>scandale</ets>, fr. L. <ets>scandalum</ets>, Gr. <?/, a snare laid
for an enemy, a stumbling block, offense, scandal: cf. OE.
<ets>scandle</ets>, OF. <ets>escandle</ets>. See
<er>Slander</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Offense caused or experienced;
reproach or reprobation called forth by what is regarded as wrong,
criminal, heinous, or flagrant: opprobrium or disgrace.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O, what a <qex>scandal</qex> is it to our crown,⟦br⟧
That two such noble peers as ye should jar!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I] have brought <qex>scandal</qex>⟦br⟧
To Israel, diffidence of God, and doubt⟦br⟧
In feeble hearts.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Reproachful aspersion; opprobrious censure;
defamatory talk, uttered heedlessly or maliciously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You must not put another <qex>scandal</qex> on him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My known virtue is from <qex>scandal</qex> free.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Equity)</fld> <def>Anything alleged in pleading
which is impertinent, and is reproachful to any person, or which
derogates from the dignity of the court, or is contrary to good
manners.</def> <rj><au>Daniell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Defamation; detraction; slander; calumny;
opprobrium; reproach; shame; disgrace.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1283 pr=PCP --></p>

<p><ent>Scandal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scandal
<hw>Scan"dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
treat opprobriously; to defame; to asperse; to traduce; to
slander.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I do fawn on men and hug them hard⟦br⟧
And after <qex>scandal</qex> them.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To scandalize; to offend.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bp. Story.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To defame; traduce; reproach; slander;
calumniate; asperse; vilify; disgrace.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scandalize</ent>⟦br⟧
